  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The goal is to make the money appear as though it comes from a legitimate source.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is prosecuted under federal law, primarily under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- **Severe fines**: Individuals convicted of money laundering can face fines of up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater. For businesses, fines can be even higher.\n- **Imprisonment**: A conviction for money laundering can result in a prison sentence of up to **20 years** per violation, depending on the circumstances and the amount of money involved.\n- **Asset forfeiture**: Authorities may seize assets that are linked to the money laundering scheme.\n\nMoney laundering is taken very seriously because it often facilitates other serious crimes, such as drug trafficking, terrorism, tax evasion, and corruption. If you\u2019re involved in or accused of money laundering, it\u2019s crucial to seek legal advice from an experienced attorney.",
